  <entry>
    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Rails and PostgreSQL]]></title>
    <link href="http://zekus.github.io/blog/2010/06/21/rails-and-postgresql/"/>
    <updated>2010-06-21T23:17:54+02:00</updated>
    <id>http://zekus.github.io/blog/2010/06/21/rails-and-postgresql</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Complaining, screaming, sweating, swearing &hellip;. why it doesnt work &hellip; jeeeeeezzz</p>

<figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>/opt/local/lib/ruby/gems/1.8/gems/activerecord-2.3.8/lib/active_record/connection_adapters/abstract/connection_specification.rb:76:in </span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>establish_connection&#8217;: Please install the postgres adapter:</p>

<figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>gem install activerecord-postgres-adapter</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p> (no such file to load &mdash; active_record/connection_adapters/postgres_adapter) (RuntimeError)
&#8220;`</p>

<p>And then a light &hellip; &ldquo;I upgraded postgresql recently!&rdquo;</p>

<p>Just reinstall the postgres gem and you are done&hellip;</p>

<p>What a night!</p>
]]></content>
